{
  "texts": [
    "Psychological and behavioral critiqueThe traversal of preceding EU efforts exposed minimal incorporation of insights from psychology and behavioral science into countering mechanisms enabling real-world disinformation proliferation.",
    "The non-binding CPD lacked obligations around transparent algorithmic systems that exploit engagement and vulnerabilities, while the ECD enabled opaque amplification of emotionally charged content to continue unchecked [170].",
    "This risks perpetuating blindspots around the outsized influence of partisan biases, opaque algorithmic harms from engagement-maximizing systems, and emotional appeals enabling the spread of disinformation [41,78].Bias and Identity Its reliance on post-hoc content corrections and debunking through notice-and-takedown procedures (Code: NTD) underestimates robust behavioral evidence revealing the outsized influence of preemptive friction nudges counteracting confirmation tendencies [94,147], motivated reasoning [137], or identity-protective cognition [18] through induced self-reflection rather than external dispute (Article 27).",
    "Provisions emphasize metaphorical notions of \"virality\" instead of granular technical factors like source credibility and message exposure frequencies psychologically enabling belief formation (Articles 26-27, Codes: NTD, RA) [63,64,78].Credibility and Engagement Additionally, oversight limitations enable engagement-maximizing ranking systems to exploit cognitive capacity gaps constraining users' systematic evaluation of information credibility when exposed to disproportionate volumes of borderline unreliable content [24] (Article 29, Code: RA).",
    "This propensity risks enabling various contextual and demographic inclusion/exclusion harms [61] from opacity."
  ]
}